SIMPLE: elegiac
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Elegiac
<hw>E*le"gi*ac</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>elegiacus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧l⟦eacute⟧giaque</ets>. See <er>Elegy</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to elegy, or written in elegiacs; plaintive;
expressing sorrow or lamentation; <as>as, an <ex>elegiac</ex> lay;
<ex>elegiac</ex> strains.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Elegiac</qex> griefs, and songs of love.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Used in elegies; <as>as, <ex>elegiac</ex> verse; the
<ex>elegiac</ex> distich or couplet, consisting of a dactylic hexameter
and pentameter.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elegiac</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Elegiac
<hw>E*le"gi*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Elegiac
verse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elegiacal</ent>⟦br⟧
